{{short description|American actor}} {{Infobox person | name = Augustus Carney | image = AugustusCarney.jpg | caption = | birth_date = 1870 | birth_place = Ireland | death_date = 1920 | death_place = | birthname = | occupation = Actor | spouse = | yearsactive = ca. 1900–16 }}
'''Augustus Carney''' (1870 – 1920) was an American actor during the early 1900s. Born in Ireland in 1870, he got his start in vaudeville before entering the film industry. In his short seven-year career he appeared in over 130 films, mostly [[short film|shorts]].
==Life and career== He began in vaudeville<ref name=allmovie>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/augustus-carney-p285137 | publisher=AllMovie | title=Augustus Carney, Biography | last=Wollstein | first=Hans J. | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> and entered films in 1909 with a featured role in a [[Ben Turpin]] comedy [[short film|short]], ''Tag Day''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0354954/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_132 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Tag Day (1909) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> He had been discovered by [[Broncho Billy Anderson]], one of the founders of [[Essanay Studios]], and was soon starring in comedy shorts for the studio. Beginning in 1910, he co-starred with [[Victor Potel]] in a series of shorts as the characters Hank and Lank (played by Carney and Potel, respectively).<ref name=imdb>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0138771/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Augustus Carney (1870–1920) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> The series lasted for two years, after which Carney developed the character of "Alkali Ike." The character starred in its own series of shorts, such as 1911's ''[[Alkali Ike's Auto]]'' (which is still extant), and which co-starred [[Harry Todd]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0002610/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_103 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Alkali Ike's Auto (1911) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> as well as appearing in many of the popular episodes of the series of film shorts featuring "Broncho Billy", which were directed by and starred Anderson.<ref name=imdb /> He also appeared in the Broncho Billy series as other characters, such as Doctor A. Carney in 1911's ''Broncho Billy's Adventure'',<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0001518/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_88 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Broncho Billy's Adventure (1911) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> and as a cowboy in 1911's ''Broncho Billy's Christmas Dinner''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0001519/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_89 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Broncho Billy's Christmas Dinner (1911) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> The Alkali Ike series became so popular that Essanay began merchandising Ike action figures.<ref name=allmovie/> While the series was running, Carney starred in other shorts for Essanay, such as ''Hubby's Scheme'' (1911),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0364418/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_91 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Hubby's Scheme (1911) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> 1911's ''A Hungry Pair'' (again co-starring Potel),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0373913/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_100 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=A Hungry Pair (1911) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> ''The Bandit's Child'' (1912 - which also starred Anderson and Todd),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0375581/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_79 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=The Bandit's Child (1912) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> and ''Hypnotism in Hicksville'' (1913).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0338116/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_54 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=Hypnotism in Hicksville (1913) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> His last appearance as Alkali Ike was released in January 1914, ''The Awakening at Snakeville''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0202804/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_27 | publisher=Internet Movie Database | title=The Awakening at Snakeville (1914) | accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref> When he asked for a higher salary and was refused, Carney left Essanay and went to work at [[Universal Studios|Universal Film Manufacturing Company]] (now known as Universal Studios). There he created the character of "Universal Ike," which was identical to Alkali Ike, but that name was owned by Essanay.<ref name=allmovie /> He made 16 films for Universal based on this character in 1914;<ref name=imdb /> however, his requests for additional pay led to his being fired by Universal that same year.<ref name=allmovie /> After his departure from Universal, he made several more shorts at various studios and appeared in only four feature films in 1915-16. Three of those features, ''The Absentee'' (1915), ''The Failure'' (1915), and ''[[Martyrs of the Alamo]]'' (1915), were directed by [[Christy Cabanne]]. His final film appearance was in a supporting role in 1916's ''Blue Blood and Red'', which was directed by [[Raoul Walsh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=13977 | title=Blue Blood and Red: Detail View | publisher=American Film Institute | accessdate= August 3, 2015}}</ref>
Carney left the film industry in 1916 and died four years later in 1920 at the age of 50.<ref name=allmovie />
